What is the structure of your dataset?

The White Wine Quality dataset consists of 13 variables and 4898 observations. The first variable is an “id” of wines, so it will be used only for references.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

My main feature of interest is the wine quality. I will investigate how different chemical (and not only) wine parameters affect the wine quality.

I see that the most popular quality mark is 6. More than 2000 wine types are of this quality. I also see that the minimal quality is 3 and the best quality is 9. The quality distribution appears to be close to normal.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

As I saw from above, there are the following chemical and physical parameters-variables that I want to investigate further:

  1. Fixed acidity;
  2. Volatile acidity;
  3. Citric acid;
  4. Residual sugar;
  5. Chlorides;
  6. Free sulfur dioxide;
  7. Total sulfur dioxide;
  8. Density;
  9. pH;
  10. Sulphates;
  11. Alcohol.

Let’s take a more closer look at all of them one by one:

Bivariate Analysis

Now let me check for relationship between different variables in my dataset. First I made a ggpairs() for all my variables except ‘id’ and manually made ones (‘qual’ and ‘sweetness’). It appeared to be badly readable, but I noticed the most important correlations from it.

Following the advice of my previous reviewer I used the corrplot and draw a representation of all correlations in my dataset. Dear reviewer, thank you very much! I appreciate your advice!

It makes very clear that we have relationship between + alcohol and density; + residual.sugar and density; + residual.sugar and alcohol; + pH and fixed.acidity; + free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide and some others.

This type of a plot is very easy-readable, demonstrative and self-explanatory.

Now I will split the ggpairs() into two plots to make it more readable:

Now the second part:

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

I didn’t notice any strong or even moderate relationship between the wine quality and other features. However I noticed: 1. weak correlation between ‘quality’ and ‘alcohol’ with the Pearson’s r of 0.4356. It means that the bigger the ‘alcohol’ value is, the higher is the wine quality mark. It doesn’t mean any causation; 2. even weaker correlation between ‘quality’ and ‘density’ with r of -0.3071. It means that the wine quality grows when ‘density’ declines. Again, no causation; 3. there are a few other slight correlations with ‘quality’: + chlorides, r = -0.21; + volatile.acidity, r = -0.195; + total.sulphur.dioxide, r = -0.175.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I observed relationship between the following variables: 1. ‘alcohol’ and ‘density’, r = -0.78. This can be explained by physics: alcohol has a lower density than water, so the more alcohol we have, the less the total density will be; 2. ‘total.sulfur.dioxide’ and ‘free.sulfur.dioxide’, r = 0.616. Based on the names, I suspect that ‘free.sulfur.dioxide’ could be a subset of ‘total.sulfur.dioxide’; 3. ‘density’ and ‘total.sulfur.dioxide’, r = 0.53;

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is seen between ‘density’ and ‘residual.sugar’, r = 0.839. This is a strong correlation indeed. It can be explained by the same physics as well.

Now let me subset only good wine and make a separate ggpairs() for it. What will I see?

Let me have a similar look at bad wine. Again, I subset bad wine and look at relationship between all variables using ggpairs().

Next I took a deep look at the results of ggpairs for good wine and for bad wine. Literally I printed out two pictures, put them next to each other and studied them. Plots are still quite small at the A4 sheet, but I noticed that some plots for the same variables look differently for good wine and bad wine.

It makes me think that there might be a relationship between ‘quality’ and some combination of these variables (such as ratio, for example).

Reflection

The white wine quality dataset contains information on 4898 wine types acroess eleven variables. First I explored single variables and created some of my own. Then I explored pairs of variables and investigated some of the notes I made on plots. Finally I did some multi-variable research and built a linear model to predict the wine quality.

I didn’t find any strong trends in my dataset. However there were some relationship found between the wine quality and other variables, such as alcohol, density, chlorides and a couple of others. I’d like to note that as the wine quality grows, the amount of chlorides decreases as does the chlorides variation.

I found out that the best wine is either dry or semi-dry.

I noted relationship - and sometimes strong! - between other variables in my dataset, such as density vs. residual.sugar, alcohol vs. density. This relationship can be explained by physics.

I also noted that wines of a moderate quality bring a lot of noise to the plots. It’s easire to see differences in characteristics of bad and good wine if the moderate ones are excluded from the analysis.

My linear model appeared to be poor and doesn’t worth serious mentioning. I really hope to learn more about models in the next course!

I’d like to point out one limitation of the dataset. It appears to contain numerous duplicate values. Before fitting a linear model I removed such rows, but it didn’t greatly improve the model.

Finally I believe that the wine quality measurement is a quite subjective task. There could be other variables that affect the expert’s perception of the quality, such as smell, wine age, etc. Such variables aren’t included into the dataset.
